{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5ed1c22c-3d39-4beb-9553-ceeaf686942a","content":"This is a **TUnit** project using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` instead of `--filter`. The command is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\n- `--` separates `dotnet test` args from MTP args\n- The treenode path format is `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<test>`\n- `/**/SmsNotificationTests/**` matches the class at any depth and includes all its tests\n\nThis will run only `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"06cc0732-f2e0-4b34-8cea-11782a305e12","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, you use `--treenode-filter` to filter tests. To filter by class name, the syntax would be:\n\n```\ndotnet run --treenode-filter \"/**/*SmsNotificationTests*\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit runs via `dotnet run` not `dotnet test` by default since it uses MTP. But the user asked about `dotnet test`.\n\nActually, with MTP-based runners, `dotnet test` should work too. \n\nThe treenode filter path format is `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<test>`, and when using `dotnet test` with MTP, I need to pass the filter through with `--` as a separator before the MTP-specific arguments. I'm working through the exact treenode filter syntax—the simpler wildcard pattern `/**/SmsNotificationTests/**` should work for filtering by class name when passed after `--` in the dotnet test command. I think I should defer to the run-tests skill since it has specialized knowledge about TUnit's filtering syntax.","outputTokens":774,"requestId":"CFDF:B84BF:1468056:17D3EF0:69EC178D"},"id":"00cccff9-004a-40c5-b1c4-2c44831b1757","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:23:41.310Z","parentId":"a78799eb-c4d0-4c61